<font color="#FF0000">DOC SPATZ'S  PARTS I &amp; II</font><br>
<tt>Sat May 17  0:36:55 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Doc Spatz,<br><br>
OK, now you really have me thinking. I admire your courage to have shared Parts I &amp; II. I know what it takes to pass through the gauntlet and share &quot;the other side&quot;. Guts. I am beginning to understand that our experiences have more connection than I had previously understood. <br><br>
In conversation with a very solid psychologist a few days ago, we examined my thoughts about &quot;protestors&quot; and my unfortunate experience outside the doors at Oakland in 1970.<br>
She made the point that those who treated returning Vietnam Veterans as less than dirt were a small cowardly minority. Most of the country was protesting the Vietnam War in determined constructive ways. Intellectually, I understand this. Emotionally, I still hurt real bad, and that clearly clouds a perception of reality long elusive but one about which I must work very hard to understand. It is still difficult for me to handle the label of &quot;baby killer&quot;, among others. I was devistated and hurt to the core.<br><br>
In Part I you said:<br><br>
&quot;I toured the battlefields within days, saw melted tanks,<br>
a desert filled with shoes, body parts, and death.&quot;<br><br>
*In this, we have a common ground.*<br><br>
&quot;I also saw a county victorious in a &quot;just&quot; war.&quot;<br><br>
*This is the propagandized lie during the Vietnam War.*<br><br>
&quot;I felt more than ever that the &quot;unjust&quot; war of Viet Nam was wrong, and had to be stopped. Something clicked in me, and I returned to face and fight it out with Local Board #125.&quot;<br><br>
*I admire you for doing this.*<br><br>
I made my second annual pilgrimage to The Wall in DC last weekend. I will share my thoughts about that here in a few days. I am still a little shakey about it. If it were not for the &quot;good&quot; protestors, such as yourself, The Wall would be far larger than it is, and I might have been chiseled on it myself. In reality, this is a testament for you too. I know it is oblique, but I really mean it.<br><br>
This is a very large leap of faith for me. I still have anger to resolve about the conduct of the government and the &quot;protestors&quot;, but I must thank you for your courage which has helped me take a few small first steps.<br><br>
Thank you, Doc.<br><br>
Art  
